U.S. Small Business Administration Loans¶

Lab Assignment One: Exploring Table Data

Mark Brubaker

Business Understanding¶

The Small Business Administration (SBA) was created in 1953 to make loans more accessible to small businesses and less risky for banks. Small business fail at a high rate making any loan they take out inherently risky. In order to mitigate this risk the SBA will guarantee a portion of the loan. This means that if the business defaults on the loan the SBA will pay the bank the guaranteed amount. This allows banks to make loans to small businesses that they would not otherwise make. These loans are crucial for many small businesses to get started and grow.

Small businesses are a major part of the U.S. economy. In 2015 they employed 58.9 million people and accounted for 99.7% of all U.S. businesses. Small businesses are also responsible for 54.2% of all U.S. sales. Investing in these businesses is a good way to stimulate the economy and create jobs. The SBA loans are a major part of this investment.

It's clear that striking a balance between incentivising small businesses and mitigating risk for banks investing them is very important. By analyzing historical data on SBA loans that have already been accepted and either paid off or defaulted we can get a better understanding of how to strike this balance. There are many factors that can be used to predict the likelihood of a loan defaulting and by exploring how each of these these factors impact the chance of a loan defaulting we can better understand which loans should be accepted and which should be rejected.

Both the SBA and a bank need to accept a loan in order for a small business to receive funding. A model predicting the likeliness of default would be useful for both parties even though they have different goals. The SBA wants to give opportunities to as many small businesses as possible in order to create jobs and stimulate the economy. A bank wants to accept as many of these loans as they can assuming the risk is low enough. An accurate model predicting the likeliness of default would allow both parties to make better decisions.

Measure of Success¶

A strict measure of success for a model would be its ability to accurately predict if a loan would default or not. However a model does not need to be perfect to still be useful. For banks, the model would only need to be accurate enough so that the successfully paid loans could offset the losses from bad predictions. Given that a large portion of every loan is guaranteed by the SBA, this margin for error is likely quite large. For the SBA, the model would need to be accurate enough to ensure that the loans they accept are likely to be paid off. The risk is just the cost of investing in small businesses and the potential reward of jobs and economic growth is easy to justify as worth it. Obviously, for both parties every bit more accurate the model is the less money is lost.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.simplefilter('ignore', FutureWarning)
warnings.simplefilter('ignore', RuntimeWarning)

# set pandas to display not using scientific notation
pd.set_option('display.float_format', lambda x: '%.2f' % x)

# read first 10000 rows of the csv file
# df = pd.read_csv('../Data/SBAnational.csv', low_memory=False, nrows=100000)
df = pd.read_csv('../Data/SBAnational.csv', low_memory=False)

# drop duplicate rows
df.drop_duplicates(keep='first', inplace=True)

# drop rows where BalenceGross is not 0
# this means that the loan has neither been paid off nor defaulted
df = df[df['BalanceGross'].str.strip() == '$0.00']

# drop rows where NAICSCode is 0
# there are enough missing values in this column that it cannot be reliably imputed
df = df[df['NAICS'] != 0]

# divide remaining NAICS codes by 100 to get the first two digits
# the first two digits of the NAICS code are the industry code
df['NAICS'] = df['NAICS'].astype(int) // 10000

# drop rows where NewExist is 0 then
# subtract 1 from NewExist to make it 0-based
df = df[df['NewExist'] != 0]
df['NewExist'] = df['NewExist'] - 1

# drop columns that are not needed
df = df.drop(['City', 'Bank', 'LoanNr_ChkDgt', 'Name', 'ApprovalDate', 'DisbursementDate', 'ChgOffDate', 'BalanceGross'], axis=1)

# convert Yes/No and PIF/CHGOFF to 1/0 floats
# floats is temporary, will be converted to ints later after imputing missing values
df['RevLineCr'] = df['RevLineCr'].map({'Y': 1, 'N': 0, '1' : 1, '0' : 0})
df['LowDoc'] = df['LowDoc'].map({'Y': 1, 'N': 0})
df['MIS_Status'] = df['MIS_Status'].map({'P I F': 1, 'CHGOFF': 0})

# remove rows with missing MIS_Status
# this is the target variable and shouldnt be imputed   
df = df[df['MIS_Status'].notnull()]

# for franchiseCode set all values over 1 to 1
df['FranchiseCode'] = df['FranchiseCode'].astype(int)
df['FranchiseCode'] = df['FranchiseCode'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 1 else 0)

# convert dollar amounts to floats
df['DisbursementGross'] = df['DisbursementGross'].str.replace('$', '').str.replace(',', '').str.replace('\.00', '').astype(float)
df['ChgOffPrinGr'] = df['ChgOffPrinGr'].str.replace('$', '').str.replace(',', '').str.replace('\.00', '').astype(float)
df['GrAppv'] = df['GrAppv'].str.replace('$', '').str.replace(',', '').str.replace('\.00', '').astype(float)
df['SBA_Appv'] = df['SBA_Appv'].str.replace('$', '').str.replace(',', '').str.replace('\.00', '').astype(float)
df['ApprovalFY'] = df['ApprovalFY'].astype(int)

# remove outliers from Term, NoEmp, CreateJob, and RetainedJob
# remove where value is greater or less than 3 standard deviations from the mean
df = df[np.abs(df['Term'] - df['Term'].mean()) <= (3 * df['Term'].std())]
df = df[np.abs(df['NoEmp'] - df['NoEmp'].mean()) <= (3 * df['NoEmp'].std())]
df = df[np.abs(df['CreateJob'] - df['CreateJob'].mean()) <= (3 * df['CreateJob'].std())]
df = df[np.abs(df['RetainedJob'] - df['RetainedJob'].mean()) <= (3 * df['RetainedJob'].std())]

A lot happens in the above cell.

Almost all of it is transforming the existing data into a more useable form.

Duplicates are removed. This is done before most processing and drops so as much information as possible can be used to find matches. If done later this may end up dropping unique loans that appear similar after things like business and bank name are removed. It is possible, although not likely, that a business may have had two identical loans accepted at the same time. Few enough rows are removed here that such a loss would have negligee impact on the resulting visualizations or predictions.

A number of rows are dropped. Without going into detail about every one they all fall into one of two catagories; Not relevant or too much missing to impute. A number of rows for various attributes are also dropped because there is either too much missing to impute or it could not be reliably imputed from existing data.

NAICS codes are truncated to extract just the fist two digits. These digits designate industry and are useful. The lost digits provide too much detail to be useful.

Franchise codes are turned into a boolean value. Both 0 and 1 designate no franchise and all other number are tell about the franchise. Only a small percent of all loans were given to franchises so I turned the attribute into 0 for no franchise and 1 for a franchise. This makes the attribute more reliable and useful.

Some attributes have their outliers removed. It is possible that they are real values but they skew any graph they are a part of too much to be useful for visualization and it is impossible to check their validity.

In [ ]:
# discertizing SBA_Appv for the purpose of imputing make the imputed values more evenly distributed
# the discertized version is only temporary
df['SBA_Appv_Disc'] = pd.cut(df['SBA_Appv'], 10, labels=False)

In order to use SBA_Appv to group by for imputing I briefly discretized it. I only did this for SBA_Appv and not GrAppv because they convey very similar types of information and I didn't want the groups that were being used for imputing to get too small.

In [ ]:
df_grouped = df.groupby(by=['Term', 'ApprovalFY', 'SBA_Appv_Disc'])
# print the average group size
print(round(df_grouped.size().mean(), 4))
func = lambda grp: grp.fillna(grp.median()) # within groups, fill using median (define function to do this)
df_imputed = df_grouped.transform(func) # apply impute and transform the data back

# Extra step: fill any deleted columns from the operation
col_deleted = list( set(df.columns) - set(df_imputed.columns)) # in case the median operation deleted columns
df_imputed[col_deleted] = df[col_deleted]

# drop any rows that still had missing values after grouped imputation
df_imputed.dropna(inplace=True)

# 5. Rearrange the columns
df_imputed = df_imputed[['State', 'Zip', 'BankState', 'NAICS', 'ApprovalFY', 'Term', 'NoEmp', 'NewExist', 'CreateJob', 'RetainedJob', 'FranchiseCode', 'UrbanRural', 'RevLineCr', 'LowDoc', 'DisbursementGross', 'MIS_Status', 'ChgOffPrinGr', 'GrAppv', 'SBA_Appv']]

I selected median as the best way to determine the value of RevLineCr in each group because it will return either 1 or 0, keeping RevLineCr a boolean value. The size of each group ended up being around 60 which is big enough for any imputed value to be statistically significant while still letting each group be unique and specific

Percent revolving line of credit before and after imputation
Before: 28.82%
After: 28.96%

I tried both methods to impute the missing data and settled on split apply combine for two main reasons. First, by trying on small samples of the data this produced better results after carefully picking what features to group by. Secondly, thought the tests I realized that KNN was not a viable strategy for filling in the missing values in a reasonable amount of time with a dataset of this size. Revolving line of credit was missing by far the most data so I used it as a gauge for how well missing values were imputed. The difference between the percent with RevLineCr before and after is just over 1/10 of 1% which I decided was close enough. Over the process of imputing missing values about 700 rows were lost. This is a small enough percent of the data I decided it was negligible.

The most obvious correlation is between how much money was approved, how much of it is covered by the government and how much money was actually loaned. There's a dark square at the cross of Term and RevLineCr which makes sense because a longer term loan is more likely to have a plan to pay it off set up, while a very short term loan is more likely to be set up to be paid of all at once. Term is correlated with a number of values, especially the ones related to money. This makes sense as a larger loan is likely to be set up over a longer period of time so each payment is smaller.

# make the plot look nicer
plt.xlabel('Approval Fiscal Year')

This graph is an expansion of the previous one, further breaking down each year by how many loans were either paid off or defaulted and how that rate changed over time. As expected the rate of defaults climbs slowly as it gets closer to the recession, with a peak at 2007 and a similar rate in 2008. After this the default rate drops down again. It can be assumed the high rate of default in the 1980's are outliers as there is very little data there. A different approach to take is which industries default at higher rates

This graph show how many loans were granted to each industry broken down by if they were paid off or defaulted and sorted by default rate. There is a high amount of variance in default rate by industry. The default rate of an industry is loosely tied to a handful of factors like barriers to entry and how stable income in that industry is. For example, retail trade and construction income are both dependent of consumer demand and it is shown through the higher default rate. Meanwhile industries like health care, agriculture, and mining all have very stable customers and will be more likely to have a income stable enough to consistently pay off a loan. These industries also require significantly more capital and planning, both of which are corralled with a lower default rate.

import geopandas as gpd

In this map each state is colored by how likely a business from that state is to default on their loan. In general the more populous states tend to have higher default rates, with Florida being particularly high. Each state has a local economy that greatly effects how well a business there will perform. A reflection of the industry data can be seen seen here as some states commonly attract more stable industries like agriculture. This leads to them having a lower default rate.

Here the percentage of loans that are from a bank that is different than the business's state is graphed. Alongside is the collective default rate for same state and out-of-state loans. Most of the states that have a high discrepancy between the default rate of businesses and of loans offered by banks in that state can be accounted for by many loans not coming from their local state. DC as an outlier in this graph also makes sense because it is very small and most of its infrastructure is government related. This would cause most DC businesses to travel to nearby states to get a loan instead. Arguably, the more interesting thing revealed here is that getting a loan from out of state significantly increases default rate.

How does loan term affect the likelihood of default?¶

In [ ]:
# hist of loan term on ax
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

ax = df_imputed.Term.hist(bins=30, color='steelblue')

default_rate_by_bin = []

# add value labels on top of bars of default rate
for p in ax.patches:
    # get the loans that match the bin
    loans = df_imputed[(df_imputed.Term >= p.get_x()) & (df_imputed.Term < p.get_x() + p.get_width())]
    # get the default rate
    default_rate = 1 - loans.MIS_Status.mean()
    # add the value label small
    ax.annotate('{:.1f}%'.format(default_rate * 100), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2, p.get_height() * 1.01), ha='center', va='bottom', size=6)
    # add the default rate to the list
    default_rate_by_bin.append(default_rate)

num_colors = 30
# map from blue to dark blue log scale
cm = plt.get_cmap('Blues')
# get only the dark half of the color map
blues = cm(np.linspace(0.5, 1, num_colors))
# evenly space the blues over the number of bins
colors = blues[np.linspace(0, num_colors - 1, len(ax.patches)).astype(int)]

# sort each bar by its default rate and color it accordingly
for i, bar in enumerate(plt.gca().patches):
    bar.set_color(colors[int(default_rate_by_bin[i] * num_colors)])

# add a legend for the colors as a colorbar
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cm, norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=0, vmax=1))
sm._A = []
cbar = plt.colorbar(sm, ticks=[0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1], ax=ax)
cbar.ax.set_yticklabels(['0%', '25%', '50%', '75%', '100%'])
cbar.set_label('Default Rate')

# make the plot look nicer
plt.title('Loan Terms')
plt.xlabel('Term (months)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Loans')

plt.xlim(df_imputed['Term'].min() - 1, df_imputed['Term'].max() + 1)
plt.grid(False)
plt.show()

One of the most important attributes is the term of the loan. This graph shows the distribution of loan terms and the rates at which they default. The two biggest peaks are at 60 months and 84 months which correspond to 5 years and 7 years. In addition to these loans being the most common they have an abnormally low default rate. There is a clear correlation between very short term loans and high default rates. It is likely that the short-sightedness of these loans reflects poor business planning and a lack of thought to the long term viability of the business. This is supported by the fact that the default rate of 5 year loans is still higher than the default rate of 7 year loans.

# plot what percent of a loan is guaranteed by the SBA
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

# plot the data
df_imputed.plot.scatter(x='GrAppv', y='PercentGuaranteed', alpha=0.01)

# make the plot look nicer
plt.xscale('log')
plt.title('Gross Disbursement vs SBA Guarantee')
plt.xlabel('Gross Disbursement ($)')
plt.ylabel('SBA Guarantee (%)')
plt.grid(False)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1500x500 with 0 Axes>

An important part of SBA loans is that a large part of the risk is mitigated by the government by covering a percent of the loan to the bank even if the business defaults. This graph makes sheds some light on how much is covered. Most obviously, the percent covered tends to be a round number between 50% and 100%, producing the clear lines on the chart. Less obviously the curved vertical lines are produced by the log scale on the x axis and a max amount to be covered. This is reflected in the information from the SBA website shown below. "For most 7(a) loan programs, the SBA can guarantee up to 85 percent of loans of $150,000 or less, and up to 75 percent of loans above $150,000. However, SBA Express loans carry a maximum of 50 percent guaranty and Export Express loans carry a maximum 90 percent guaranty. The Export Working Capital loan program and International Trade loans carry a maximum of 90 percent guaranty, up to a guaranteed amount of $4.5 million."
